english:
  title: The Hermit of Yesa Mountain
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The hermit's name was Hajae, though some called him Hade. Changhoe was his family name. His ancestors were from the land of Yongbaek. Originally his was not a compound surname, but because our tongue drawls the syllables slowly, name and family were merged and transformed together. From childhood, the hermit seemed to understand the principles of Heaven. When he took up learning, he was not confined to a single corner of knowledge. He grasped the essential direction of things, yet completed nothing fully—for he saw widely but never dug deep. As he matured, he held ambitious aspirations for advancement and recognition. The world would not grant them. This was because his nature ill-suited him to courting favor, and worse, he loved wine. After a few cups, he delighted in speaking of others' virtues and faults, whatever entered through his ear never staying behind his lips. Thus he won neither love nor esteem. Each position he obtained slipped away as quickly. Though friends pitied him and urged reform, some counseling, some reproaching, he could not accept their words. By middle age he regretted much, yet by then the world had already deemed him unfit. Opportunities closed. The hermit too relinquished all desire for this world.

    Once he said of himself: "All those with whom I have kept company were good people. Yet many went unrecognized. To win the approval of the multitude—truly, how difficult." What was his shortcoming became his strength.

    In his later years, he followed a monk from Gapsa Temple, borrowed land to farm, and opened a garden he called "Sufficiency." He took the name "The Hidden Farmer of Yesa Mountain." He inscribed above his seat these words: "Your field, your garden—a debt of gratitude to the Three Treasures. Where comes sufficiency? Let it never be forgotten." Though the hermit had never favored Buddhism, he became their tenant farmer, so lamenting how his life's direction had strayed, he mocked himself.
  footnotes:
    - Yongbaek (龍伯國) likely refers to an ancient kingdom or region, possibly Goguryeo or an early Korean state.
    - The Three Treasures (三寶) in Buddhism refer to the Buddha, the Dharma (teachings), and the Sangha (monastic community).
    - Gapsa Temple (갑사) is a real Korean Buddhist temple with a long history.
    - The hermit's self-inscription plays on Confucian self-reliance while employing Buddhist concepts, reflecting the philosophical tensions of his life.
